all entries showing a modification date of 1/13/2025 at various times: .git at 4:24 PM, and the others (customAssets, Docker, l10n, model) at 3:04 PM or 3:05 PM. The view is in a standard list format, highlighting the organization of project assets for what appears to be a task management application.\n\n\n  \n In the Docker folder you will find files to help you run a container with the ORIGAM server. You can choose between Linux and Windows operating systems for the server. We will use Linux here. \n For Linux, as well as for Windows, there are two types of files created: \n \n \n CMD file \n This file contains a command for the creation of the Docker container and it may look like this: \n \n \n  docker run --env-file \u0022c:\\OrigamProjects\\MyApplication\\Docker\\myapplication.env\u0022 ^\n    -it --name myapplication ^\n    -v \u0022c:\\OrigamProjects\\MyApplication\\model\u0022:/home/origam/projectData/ ^\n    -p 443:443 ^\n    origam/server:master-latest.linux\n  \n This command links the configuration file, names the Docker container, maps the local project directory in your file system to the one in the Linux server that will be created, and sets up the server port. \n \n   The ORIGAM version that will be used by default to create this container is set to  master-latest , but we recommend using an older stable version instead and specifying it in the script, for example  origam/server:2026.1.0.4131.linux . \nSee the list of releases  here . \n \n \n \n ENV file \n This file contains configuration that is used in the CMD file. Here is an example: \n \n \n  OrigamSettings__DefaultSchemaExtensionId=09831214-2e3a-4142-a81f-8a566aeb0020\nOrigamSettings__DataConnectionString=Data Source=host.docker.internal,1433;Initial Catalog=myapplication;Integrated Security=False;User ID=mydbuser;Password=mydbpassword;Pooling=True;Encrypt=False\nOrigamSettings__Name=myapplication\nCustomAssetsConfig__PathToCustomAssetsFolder=/home/origam/projectData/customAssets\nCustomAssetsConfig__RouteToCustomAssetsFolder=/customAssets\nDatabaseType=mssql\nExternalDomain_SetOnStart=https://localhost\nTZ=Europe/Prague\n  \n We will not go into the details of this configuration here, but if you want to know more about this topic or you need to run a version older than 2025.11, you can refer to the  documentation , as the parameter notation is slightly different. \n Under normal circumstances, you don\u2019t need to make any changes to any of these files and you can use them as generated. \n   Docker container creation \n In order to create a Docker container with the ORIGAM server, you just need to run the CMD file and do it as a system administrator. \n \n Important note: \nBefore running the command, please make sure the DB server you set up in your ORIGAM project is up and running. If needed, check the article dedicated to this topic  here . \n \n Now open your Command Prompt (CMD) in Windows, go to the Docker directory in your project and run the CMD file typing, for example: \n  myapplication_Linux.cmd\n  \n \n    MacOS users need to convert the file to a Shell Script and run it in Mac Terminal or create a Docker container with a Windows image using a virtual machine to run the script. \n \n If everything runs in order, at the end of all the generated code, you will get a notification that your Docker container ( Application ) is started. \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:39:30"},"vector":[0.0073365695,-0.015312022,-0.071062274,0.0031298588,-0.018120296,-0.021697544,-0.0075910003,-0.015465931,0.009334241,0.006488063,0.017006693,0.030767838,-0.039807558,-0.0035149623,-0.011596798,-0.05221364,0.010058693,0.023942804,0.0317594,-5.0814055E-05,-0.0018985947,-0.029232701,0.08329144,0.037012268,0.012581474,0.02286621,0.001008856,-0.04264015,0.030855924,-0.0076795714,-0.029192066,-0.051836096,-0.03248393,-0.030634897,0.022016305,0.0